Execute the command kubectl describe deployment and locate MaxUnavailable under the RollingUpdateStrategy section in the deployment details.

11.Change the deployment strategy to Recreate.

Delete and re-create the deployment if necessary. Only update the strategy type for the existing deployment.

Run the command kubectl edit deployment frontend to modify the necessary field. Additionally, ensure that you delete the properties of rollingUpdate found at spec.strategy.rollingUpdate.

12.Upgrade the application by configuring the deployment to use the image kodekloud/webapp-color:v3.

Do not delete and re-create the deployment. Only set the new image name for the existing deployment.

Execute the command: kubectl edit deployment frontend to modify the necessary field.

To upgrade the application image to kodekloud/webapp-color:v3 without recreating the deployment, run:
kubectl set image deploy frontend simple-webapp=kodekloud/webapp-color:v3
This updates the container image on the existing frontend deployment. Because the deployment strategy is Recreate, Kubernetes terminates all existing Pods and then starts new Pods using the v3 image, which can cause the application to be briefly unavailable.
Alternatively, you can edit the deployment:
kubectl edit deployment frontend
Then, in the spec.template.spec.containers section, modify:
image: kodekloud/webapp-color:v2
to:
image: kodekloud/webapp-color:v3
Save and exit to apply the change. The Pods will be terminated and recreated simultaneously with the new image due to the Recreate strategy.
After the update, you can verify:
kubectl describe deployment frontend | grep Image
kubectl get pods -o wide
This will show you the updated image, reflecting the change to kodekloud/webapp-color:v3.

13.Run the script curl-test.sh once more and observe the failures. Please wait for the new application to become fully operational. You should notice that the requests no longer reach both versions.
Execute the script located at /root/curl-test.sh using the following command:
bash /root/curl-test.sh

